{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:20:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:20:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18128"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18128"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.94,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10842"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59069"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1286"},{"type":"tags","id":"1537"},{"type":"tags","id":"2143"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after falling onto his outstretched hand while playing basketball. He reports pain in his wrist, particularly on the thumb side, and has difficulty moving his wrist. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the anatomical snuffbox of his right wrist. An X-ray of the wrist is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following carpal bones is most likely fractured in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Triquetrum","Scaphoid","Hamate","Pisiform","Lunate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and mechanism of injury in this scenario are highly suggestive of a \u003Cstrong\u003Escaphoid\u003C/strong\u003E fracture. The scaphoid is the most commonly fractured carpal bone, often resulting from a fall on an outstretched hand. Tenderness in the anatomical snuffbox is a classic sign of a scaphoid fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELunate\u003C/strong\u003E fractures are less common and typically present with different clinical features, such as wrist instability or dislocation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriquetrum\u003C/strong\u003E fractures are the second most common carpal fractures but usually result from direct trauma to the dorsum of the wrist, not a fall on an outstretched hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHamate\u003C/strong\u003E fractures are rare and often associated with sports involving a bat or racket, presenting with pain on the ulnar side of the wrist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPisiform\u003C/strong\u003E fractures are uncommon and usually result from a direct blow to the hypothenar eminence, not a fall on an outstretched hand.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The scaphoid bone is the most commonly fractured carpal bone.","Scaphoid fractures often occur due to a fall on an outstretched hand.","Prompt diagnosis and management of scaphoid fractures are crucial to prevent complications such as avascular necrosis."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59069"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18128"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59069"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T00:30:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T14:32:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10842"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":n